<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-297-019  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 297 019.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Feb 5 1989 v138 n47,772 pY33(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Electronic systems for the home getting smarter. (Talking -Security) (security systems) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brooks, Andree.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A 1988 marketing survey by Security Distributing and Marketingmagazine shows that one home in 12 now has some form of electronicsecurity system.andP;  The systems use sensors in doors, windows, matsand beams, connected to a central monitoring station, to warn ofimpending crises, such as intruders or a fire.andP;  The early systemsgenerated many false alarms, resulting in a number of communitiesinstituting fines for false alarms, and-or requiring registrationand licensing of such systems.andP;  The newer, advanced computerizedsystems generate fewer false alarms, and can be customized to theowner's specifications.andP;  Such systems cost in the thousands ofdollars, and should be budgeted for in terms of hook-up chargesand monthly fees as well.andP;  A booklet is available from theNational Burglar and Fire Alarm Association that offers tips onselection of security systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Security SystemsSurveillance SystemsHardware SelectionCritiqueTutorial.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>